  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>EVERQUEST : HIS RISE - CHAPTER 3</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><center><b>Chapter Three</b><br><i>A Druid. Movement. Uknown Voice.</i></center><p>
The sun was on it's last moments, pretending to fade down into the landscape, and still the gnolls had not yet made their attack.  The Qeynos Militia stood alongside the gates, as the archer's stood up top, waiting.  Everything was waiting, even the sun, or so it all seemed.  For the past two hours nothing had happened, the gnolls just stood there, waiting for something or were just too stupid to know how to attack after they had gather their forces and walked up to the enemies front porch.<p>
     As the time passed, and the air began to become colder, many men decided that the large gnoll threat wasn't that much of a threat any longer and started to pack up and head back to their homes.  The officers couldn't really tell them to stay since nothing had happened, and due to the history of the gnoll attacks they doubted anything would happen.  As these thoughts spread throughout the group, many more left as did some officers.  Thirty men now stood at the gates, as did fifteen or so archers.  However, the Qeynos Guard of the Steel Warriors still remained at the fronts, they knew not to underestimate threats of any nature, be it from a clumsy foe or an arch-mage, a threat is a threat.<p>
     Yet, from the remaining men, a young man stood staring out into the sea of gnolls, in his eyes he appeared to be hurt.  As if something ached in him, something tugging at him to feel pain, pain for nature.  From his appearance many had mistaken him for a warrior, due to his choice of scimitar, over his professions customary weapon of blunt staves.  He wore old worn leather armor, given to him as a hand down from his father's friend who when young, was a druid.  However, the original owner was an elf and the body structure of an elf and human was rather different.  This difference showed in the armor, as it hugged tightly to his body but did not hamper his movment.<p>
     Among many in town he was known as "Rusty", due to his tight fitting, rusty looking leather armor that often creaked as he moved, a nickname he did not want or enjoy.  As his true name was Dorson Refron, born in a small makeshift house within the Karana's.  Because of this upbringing, he was raised to know how it was to be poor and to love nature.  The love of nature, gave him over to Karana and to serve under him as a druid.  From that moment, he began to learn more about the druids, and at times when his parents were asleep he would sneak out and visit the druidic circle within the planes.<p>
     It was there, at the circle, where he began to learn about the craft and lore.  At night, various druids would use spells which would teleport them around the realms, this amazed Dorson to no end.  It was also here, where they taught him various spells, and taught him how to fight various beasts which surrounded the area.  He had spent many nights out in the fields with a mentor druid, and at some nights more than one would come to mentor him.  He never backed down, even if he was to the end of his wits due to lack of sleep.  Yet, this weakness was often overcome by various spells which would rejuvenate his body, for a time.  <p>
     However, if one stays at one point long enough, another takes notice.  As was the case with Dorson, for one night as he sat half awake at the circle, a halfling approached him.  After a long inquiry, the halfling introduced himself as Truven Farsun.  At hearing that name, Dorson immediately jumped to his feet.  Truven was an extremely well known throughout the druidic community, and visions of his power swam in the head of a young boy.  All Truven could do at that moment was give a quirkish halfling smile to the lad.<p>
     That night passed slowly, as Dorson recalled goals he had, events that had passed, his situation at home and with his parents.  Through it all, Truven listened intently as if he was weighing something in his mind, until Dorson ended his session with a yawn.  It was at that moment when Truven gave him a leaf, a bright shimmering leaf, and told the boy to head of to Surefall Glade as soon as possible and to give the leaf to anyone within the Glade.<p>
     Within a few days, Dorson had found the time to make the trek, even though the time didn't wish him to travel as rain poured almost non-stop the entire trip.  Yet, with the aid of traveling spells, he was able to reach the Glade within half a day.  The boy, however, was not prepared for the sheer beauty of the Glade, as he entered through a small tunnel carved through the mountain within the Qeynos Hills.  <p>
     His eyes had drooped, he recalled not being able to breath, just walking dumbly staring at the lush vegetation, tall trees, crystal clear and pure water, and in the background a faint crashing of a waterfall.  This was a place of peace, even the air smelled of it, that light tint of pine mixed with pure water.  It was the water that had captivated him, he had never seen water so pure, as he was raised on murky waters from the Serpent's River.  <p>
     It was at the docks when a beautiful women approached him.  He could remember little else except her beauty, for she was a wood elf dressed in finely linked armor with two swords at her waist, her perfect waist.  The elf women, however, soon got annoyed with the boy and demanded he leave, it was then when he showed her the shimmering leaf.  She gasped to say the least, and immediately took hold of the child's arm and brought him into a wooden structure.  Only again, to leave the poor child in mouth gapping awe.<p>
     Within the chambers, various other men and women walked along, and stood casting various spells, it all seemed cozy and comfortable to him.  It somehow reminded him of his home, except surrounded by utterly extravagant beauty.  It was here when the elf took him to another woman, who was in appearance a human, but her beauty rivaled that of Tunare herself, or so he imagined.  Her name was Te'Anara, who he later came to find out was the head caretaker of the druids within the Jaggedpine.<p>
     As the elf handed her the leaf, Te'Anara grinned with delight.  Within the next few hours, Dorson had been introduced to more people than he had ever thought would hold many of the same values as he had.  It also, wasn't until later that he was welcomed into his new home, and his new master, as he had arrived later during the night.  Truven, had finally selected a pupil, a child to train and to teach them the ways of nature and Karana.<p>
     Dorson sighed, regaining his bearings after the thoughts of how he found himself where he was now.  It had been hard to leave his parents, but they agreed to let him join the Jaggedpine Treefolk after discussing it with Truven.  Before he had left they held a small party for him.  It was there where he received this "rusty" looking outfit, a gift.  A gift of love, and that love is why he had never wore another set of armor since.  It was also, sadly, all they could manage to give him, next to most their own savings of twenty platinum pieces, who Truven tried to tell them that all things would be paid for.  Yet, they insisted on their son having the money, and it was then he had finally left, with small streaks of tears dripping down his cheeks.<p>
     A scream rang up next to him, immediately Dorson snapped out of his reminiscing and turned to his left.  A man had been hacked in the side by another, shock registered in the druid's eyes, and turned to look out into the field, the gnoll's were still waiting.  Confusion ran through his mind, as it seemed to be going through the minds of others at the gates.  Another scream went up into the night air, as a thud soon followed.<p>
     Dorson looked through the crowd, catching the two fallen bodies near the front entrance with small blood pools already flowing down the cracks of the stone walkway.  The creaking and chinking of armor was rising in volume as men shuffled to find an attacker.  Soon, all their eyes fell upon a tall barbarian warrior being assaulted by one of their own.  The barbarian was Dun, a local security guard of the Qeynos bank.<p>
     "Get this bastard off of me!  Stop attacking!", boomed the strong barbarian as he blocked blow after blow, afraid to aggressively assault the man in return for fear of killing him.  <p>
     "Frenko! Stop! Put yer sword away!"  Cried a man within the group amassing around the small fight, "Frenko!"<p>
     Frenko didn't even seem to notice the cries from the others within the crowd, but seemed to only hold one thing on his mind, to kill his target.  And if to kill his target was his goal, he didn't show any sign of letting up any time soon.  Dun continued to block and slash away the man's blade, but unlike Frenko the furious flurry of blades was beginning to tire the tall barbarian out, something had to be done quickly.<p>
     Dorson stepped upon the outer edge of the small bricks lining the outside of the gates, to get a better look at the two.  His mind raced, as it searched for the correct spell to use in this situation, then a cry went up that Frenko was charmed.  Charmed!  Dorson grinned, and began to move his hands and recited various words.  Soon, a white haze rose around his hands as he looked at Frenko, within the air the white haze left Dor's hands and reappeared around Frenko encasing his entire form.<p>
     Frenko took in a deep gasp, gulping in a huge amount of air, as he stumbled away from the huge barbarian.  Dun, in front of him, was still moving his huge sword in his repetitive motion of blocks, until he finally realized the attacks had ceased.  Frenko fell onto his back, breathing abnormally hard, not able to receive enough air to his lungs and body.  The crowd all gathered around him, he appeared to be in utter pain, as he laid on the floor gasping and staring up at the night's sky.<p>
     "They move!  Incoming!  Draw your swords and arrows!", called the loud gate's guard, as another man nearby blew a loud trumpet, followed later by another trumpet at another point in the city.<p>
     The circle turned their attention back to the gnolls.  A silence wept over them all, and about all that could be heard was the heavy heaving of Frenko.  The hills, had turned into a moving sea of gnolls.  Like waves as they begin to wash into shore, their numbers were almost amazing.  None had ever thought there had been so many.  Yet, as their eyes were locked on the oncoming sea of a major assault, three gnolls began to fade into view twenty yards in front of them.  Their hands already in the motions of spells, and one could hear the faint ragged voice of their incantations.<p>
     From the battlements arrows began to fly towards the closer targets.  One of the volley found it's mark, sending an arrow through the right shoulder of one of the casting gnolls, foiling his spell.  He soon regained his composure and began casting again.  Yet, by this time the other spells had been completed, and soon the entire front gate was encased in a huge, almost blindingly bright white light.  In moments, the white haze began to fade down towards the ground, just before it was encased by another white haze.<p>
     The injured gnoll's spell shot off and the haze encompassed most of the ramparts, waiting for a moment before fading out as it fell into nothingness.  At the sight, the gnoll's turned towards their comrades and began casting various spells, as the oncoming army sped for the gates.<p>
     Dorson stood motionless, unable to move, no doubt that the entire front gate had been hit with a mesmerize spell.  In this state, one often felt joy, inexplicable joy, that feeling was lessened greatly by the sight of a sea of death charging at you.  His mind raced, searching for a way to get out of this situation, until he finally relented and remained where he was staring at his death soon approaching.<p>
     The gnoll's were now within ten yards of the gate and no arrows had been shot, nothing had slowed their progress.  The small militia were sitting ducks in the way of a large army.  From down the streets, shouts were being raised but no men had arrived at the gates to reinforce what was soon to be lost.  <p>
     A gurgling cry sounded, as the first gnoll reached the Gates of Qeynos and slashed a man across his throat sending him down.  The other gnolls were now at the front gate, yet many had stayed back thirty yards or out of accurate arrow shot, as the gate was much too small to accommodate the size of the army all at once.  Though, as men fell and gnolls passed, they bumped into others.  Soon, most of the militia were no longer under the effects of the gnoll's spell.<p>
     Melee broke out, with the clashing of swords, and chinking of armor rang into the night.  Paws and boots rapped on the stone walkway, sending an echo down towards the rest of the city.  Battle cries rose into the night air, as did the frequent thud of a body hitting the pavement. <p> 
     Above the crowd, Dun stood taller than all, and wielded his huge sword with expert accuracy.  Slashing one gnoll in the upper chest, only to spin around and give another a slice that ripped the stomach from one and proceeded up to his rib cage, sending the gnoll to the ground with a mess next to it's dead form.  These gnolls, were BlackBurrow gnolls, their lack of skill was apparent, but they would serve as good tools for the upper divisions of the army that stood beyond them, to tire the men at the gate.<p>
     Dorson, stood shocked by it all, men yelled in agony and dogs barked in pain.  The melee sent him into another world, a world he had never met before, the world of war and death.  His breathing began to quicken, not knowing what to do, almost on the verge of tears searching for a spell to cast a voice sounded behind him.<p>
     "Calm thyself young druid, stand back and observe the battle with a calmness that Karana has there to provide," that voice was one he had never heard before but he did as they instructed and stood there observing the battle slowing his breaths.<p>
     "Now, find a single target, perhaps one who is in the largest struggle, here you are given a choice, does he need a healing spell, or the aid of nature to harm the attackers?" Dorson took a look in the direction of the largest fray, and of course found Dun in the middle of it all.<p>
     "I don't see much damage on him, his armor seems to be holding off most of the blows, but he is being hit occasionally," responded Dorson to the unknown voice.<p>
     "Good, so a spell that hurts the attacker is what he needs then."<p>
     Immediately Dor was in the gestures of a spell, speaking soft words.  As he spoke, small spikes swam in a green haze around his hands.  Upon the last word, a globe shimmered around Dun, the next moment he was hit, a spike struck out and attacked the gnoll, sending him into a barking fit.  Dun glanced up towards the druid and thanked him with his eyes.<p>
     "Very good, and see how he thanked you for it.  That young one, is how you stay calm within a fight.  Always occupy yourself with a way to aid them in a calm manner, as your craft allows, you're mainly aiding them.", the voice sounded calm and cool, almost in an enchanting manner.<p>
     Dor turned around, and looked for the voice, only to be greeted by a wall nearby.  Turning in a three sixty, he still saw no one next to him.  Except for a soft chuckle as an image of a man draped in a dark robe, the robe held no major markings, something uncommon for many mages, except trainees.  As Dor glanced at the man, the smile caught his attention, the man's build was above average for a caster, and seemingly larger than a normal human's but not large enough for a barbarian.  <p>
     His eyes, were almost a fiery hazel, yet his hair was a silverish white.  By no means did this man appear to need white hair yet, his face was almost young, along the border line of manhood and the elderly years.  The hair cascaded over his shoulders and down his back, yet the length was just a little past his neck.  In his hand, was a normal looking staff.  Dor had learned more about staffs during his time at the Jaggedpine than he had ever really cared to know, but he did learn that a normal looking staff in the hands of a mage, probably wasn't too normal.  <p>
     The mage before him, seemed to take notice of the observation, and raised an eyebrow.  Dor met his eyes, and stumbled for words.<p>
     "I apologize sir, I didn't mean to intrude or anything," Dor's eyes went to the ground not wanting to anger an unknown mage.<p>
     The man chuckled and tilted his head slightly, smiling until Dor's eyes raised back up from the floor.  "No need for apologies, young one," the mage looked up and glanced at the fray still continuing.  Reinforcements from the city had arrived at the gate, as another portion of gnolls had been sent up to the gate.  Returning his gaze to Dorson, he smiled and continued, "perhaps, I should introduce myself.  I am Simonic Dul'Khar, wanderer of the lands, and know many strategies of battle.  What I had just discussed with you now, is only a small bit of what you can do, but one thing is sure in all battles, stay calm."<p>
     Dorson nodded to Simonic, and just stood there as if waiting for more until he caught himself and his rudeness.  "Oh, I'm Dorson Refron, Druid of Karana, pupil to Truven Farsun," Dor halted a bit, trying to think of something more to say, but found he was utterly speechless by the sight of the man in front of him.  Truly, his appearance was amazing, specially to an untraveled commoner.<p>
     "Well met Dorson.  So, Truven finally took up a pupil did he?  Well child, you're under good hands with him, but perhaps I should convince him to teach you more about combat," at the last phrase Dorson blushed a bit, "oh, no, no Dorson, you've done a grand job thus far, but it is far from over," From the streets Ebon's voice boomed, a call to let all know that their leader was approaching.<p>
     "I'll go in search of Truven, he shouldn't be too hard to find, and if you like seeing things out of the ordinary, you're in for a huge treat," at that moment Simonic pointed over to the front of the gates. <p>
     A man armored in a yellowish tint of steel armor began to swing dual wielding swords, sending up gnoll blood into the air, slash after slash.  As Dor looked at the man behind him his mouth went agape.  The man was dressed in purple, swirling purple, armor and wielded a hammer the likes he had never seen.  Turning to look at the mage again, Dorson found him to be gone.  He had started to turn in search of the mage, but knew he would not find him, so he returned his attention back onto the battle, with a calm breath.<p>
<center>**********************************************<p>
<b>Chapter Four</b><br><i>Magic. Retreats. Rogues.</i></center><p>
     Men cheered and whooped as Ebon came into the fray, slashing the gnolls in whatever spot was open.  Behind him, stood Tonmerk a man who many probably did not recognize, except for various veterans, and when they did see him they uttered prayers to Nife.  As most of the other Steel Warriors came up to the front, the paladin's began reciting prayers and casting various spells upon themselves.  It was then, when magic hit.
<p>
